"spacer","hasAlt":true,"isDecorative":false,"isMissingAlt":false,"ariaHidden":false,"rolePresentation":false,"renderedWidth":1,"renderedHeight":2,"naturalWidth":10,"naturalHeight":10,"loading":null,"decoding":null,"altVerdict":"SUSPICIOUS","altReason":"meaningless alt text: \"spacer\"","bytes":821},{"src":"https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/images/spacer.gif","alt":"spacer","hasAlt":true,"isDecorative":false,"isMissingAlt":false,"ariaHidden":false,"rolePresentation":false,"renderedWidth":1,"renderedHeight":2,"naturalWidth":10,"naturalHeight":10,"loading":null,"decoding":null,"altVerdict":"SUSPICIOUS","altReason":"meaningless alt text: \"spacer\"","bytes":821},{"src":"https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/headers_footers/images/spacer.gif","alt":"spacer","hasAlt":true,"isDecorative":false,"isMissingAlt":false,"ariaHidden":false,"rolePresentation":false,"renderedWidth":10,"renderedHeight":1,"naturalWidth":10,"naturalHeight":10,"loading":null,"decoding":null,"altVerdict":"SUSPICIOUS","altReason":"meaningless alt text: \"spacer\"","bytes":821},{"src":"https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/images/spacer.gif","alt":" ","hasAlt":true,"isDecorative":false,"isMissingAlt":false,"ariaHidden":false,"rolePresentation":false,"renderedWidth":10,"renderedHeight":1,"naturalWidth":10,"naturalHeight":10,"loading":null,"decoding":null,"altVerdict":"DECORATIVE","altReason":"alt=\"\" (decorative)","bytes":821},{"src":"https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/images/spacer.gif","alt":" ","hasAlt":true,"isDecorative":false,"isMissingAlt":false,"ariaHidden":false,"rolePresentation":false,"renderedWidth":1,"renderedHeight":10,"naturalWidth":10,"naturalHeight":10,"loading":null,"decoding":null,"altVerdict":"DECORATIVE","altReason":"alt=\"\" (decorative)","bytes":821},{"src":"https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/figures/m720a4t.gif","alt":"TABLE. Clinical summaries of five fatal cases of neonatal coxsackievirus B1 (CVB1) infection reported to CDC — United States, 2007\nCase no.\n1\n2\n3\n4\n5\nState\nCalifornia\nCalifornia\nIllinois\nColorado\nNew Mexico\nVirus detection\nCVB1 isolated from blood\nCVB1 isolated from cerebrospinal\nfluid (CSF)\nCVB1 detected by reverse\ntranscription-polymerase chain\nreaction (RT-PCR) in CSF and\nisolated postmortem from heart\ntissue\nCVB1 detected by RT-PCR in CSF\nand in serum\nCVB1 isolated premortem from\nnasopharyngeal and rectal swabs\nand isolated postmortem from lungs\nand nasopharyngeal swab\nClinical summary\nA full-term male was born via cesarean delivery. His mother had a peripartum\nfever. The infant went home with his mother on day 5 of life. He was admitted to\nthe hospital on day 7 with thrombocytopenia, hepatitis, and myocarditis. The\ninfant died the next day. Autopsy revealed severe hepatitis with extensive\nnecrosis, severe myocarditis, and pneumonitis.\nA full-term female was born via normal spontaneous vaginal delivery. Her mother\nwas febrile during labor. The infant became febrile 36 hours after birth. She was\ndiagnosed with myocarditis, meningitis, respiratory distress, and disseminated\nintravascular coagulation on day 4 of life; she died the same day.\nA male was born via cesarean delivery at 37 weeks. His mother had\nchorioamnionitis. The infant developed fever on day 3 of life and was diagnosed\nwith severe myocarditis and hepatitis on day 5; respiratory failure and cardiovascular\ncollapse ensued on day 7. The infant received intraveneous immunoglobulin\non day 11 and was started on steroids on day 12. He died from severe\nmyocardial dysfunction on day 12.\nA full-term male was born via normal spontaneous vaginal delivery. He developed\nrespiratory problems on day 5 of life and thrombocytopenia on day 7. He\nwas diagnosed with enteroviral myocarditis on day 10 after acute cardiac\ndecompensation. Subsequently, he had multiorgan failure with hepatic and renal\ndysfunction, persistent pulmonary hemorrhage, and bilateral intracranial\nhemorrhage. He was removed from life support on day 23 and died.\nA female was born via spontaneous vaginal delivery at 34.5 weeks. Before\ndelivery, her mother had abdominal pain, fever, nausea, vomiting, and maternal/\nfetal tachycardia. The infant developed respiratory distress, requiring life support\non day 5 of life, followed by thrombocytopenia and intracranial hemorrhage on\nday 6. She died on day 7. Autopsy revealed significant frontal lobe hemorrhagic\ninfarcts, encephalitis, massive acute hepatic necrosis, interstitial edema,\nairspace hemorrhage, and patchy hyaline membranes in lungs.","hasAlt":true,"isDecorative":false,"isMissingAlt":false,"ariaHidden":false,"rolePresentation":false,"renderedWidth":641,"renderedHeight":386,"naturalWidth":641,"naturalHeight":386,"loading":null,"decoding":null,"altVerdict":"TOO_LONG","altReason":"alt text is 2645 characters — consider a caption or description","bytes":84690},{"src":"https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/figures/m720a4f.gif","alt":"FIGURE. Number of reports of coxsackievirus B1 (CVB1)\ninfection and percentage of CVB1 reports among all\nenterovirus infections with known serotypes — National\nEnterovirus Surveillance System, United States, 1970–2007","hasAlt":true,"isDecorative":false,"isMissingAlt":false,"ariaHidden":false,"rolePresentation":false,"renderedWidth":510,"renderedHeight":374,"naturalWidth":510,"naturalHeight":374,"loading":null,"decoding":null,"altVerdict":"GOOD","altReason":"present, no red flags","bytes":16241},{"src":"https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/images/spacer.gif","alt":" ","hasAlt":true,"isDecorative":false,"isMissingAlt":false,"ariaHidden":false,"rolePresentation":false,"renderedWidth":10,"renderedHeight":1,"naturalWidth":10,"naturalHeight":10,"loading":null,"decoding":null,"altVerdict":"DECORATIVE","altReason":"alt=\"\" (decorative)","bytes":821},{"src":"https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/headers_footers/images/spacer1.gif","alt":"","hasAlt":true,"isDecorative":true,"isMissingAlt":false,"ariaHidden":false,"rolePresentation":false,"renderedWidth":1,"renderedHeight":1,"naturalWidth":10,"naturalHeight"